## Selected projects in data science, machine learning, scheduling and operations research

---

### Predicting product returns
This project analyzes an online retailer's data using Python to create a classifier that predicts whether an item will be returned. The dataset is from the [Data Mining Cup 2014](https://www.data-mining-cup.com/reviews/dmc-2014/), and models such as Neural Network, XGBoost, CatBoost, and LightGBM are used to predict the returns. The top-performing model was CatBoost (GPU) with an MAE of 0.2974 on the test set, placing the solution in the top 4 of the Data Mining Cup 2014 [ranking](https://www.wi.hs-wismar.de/~cleve/vorl/dmdaten/daten/DMC/DMC2014_Ranking.pdf).

### E-commerce dashboard
E-commerce dashboard created with Plotly and Dash, providing dynamic visualization of Key Performance Indicators (KPIs). This user-friendly dashboard features advanced filtering options, enabling users to precisely tailor data based on categorical column selection and specific date ranges. To enhance the visual experience, a choropleth map is seamlessly integrated, offering a vivid representation of KPI values across geographical locations enabling users to make informed decisions based on a deeper understanding of regional trends and patterns.

### Brand perception dashboard
As part of my master's thesis, I created an interactive web-based dashboard using Dash and Plotly. The primary purpose of the dashboard was to display how consumers perceive different brands.

The first section visualizes the findings from the research paper ["Mining Brand Perceptions from Twitter Social Networks"](http://dx.doi.org/10.1287/mksc.2015.0968) -published in Marketing Science, written by Aron Culotta and Jennifer Cutler.

<img src="images/tab1.png?raw=true" />

The second section displays the impact of brand perceptions on the stock market for five well-known brands, including Apple, Coca-Cola, H&M, Nike, and Starbucks. The data used for the visualization was obtained from the social networks Twitter and StockTwits, as well as the marketing research company YouGov.


<img src="images/tab2.png?raw=true" />
